- 'Thermal' tests are those that involve temperature-related conditions;
- 'Scheduled' refers to tests that are planned but not yet completed;
- 'More than one scheduled test under their belt' means the engineer has more than one test of the same type and category scheduled.

- 'Scheduled' status refers to tests that are planned but not yet started;
- 'equipment_id' is a unique identifier for each piece of equipment;
- 'test_id' is a unique identifier for each test;
- The start date is based on the calendar year.

- 'Most recent' refers to the latest scheduled start date for each test ID;
- 'Used on more than 5 unique days' means the equipment has been scheduled on at least 6 different days;
- 'Higher pass rate than fail rate' means the number of passing tests is greater than the number of failing tests for a given test item.

- 'Pass' status in the context of test results indicates a successful outcome of the test;
- The 'test_date' is used to determine the most recent test results for each test ID;
- The pass rate is calculated as the ratio of tests with a 'Pass' status to the total number of tests.

- 'Blossomed with more than half of their flowers in full bloom' refers to more than 50% of tests passing;
- 'Average duration longer than two days' refers to an average test duration greater than 48 hours;
- 'Marked as fully grown' refers to the test schedule status being 'Completed'.

- 'Most scheduled test engineer' refers to the engineer who has the highest number of scheduled tests;
- 'Most recently calibrated equipment' refers to the equipment that has the latest calibration date;
- 'Highest humidity' and 'highest temperature' refer to the tests with the maximum recorded humidity and temperature, respectively.

- 'Temperature Chambers' are specialized pieces of equipment used to test items under various temperature conditions;
- 'High Temperature Testing' is a specialization that focuses on testing items under high-temperature conditions;
- 'Scheduled' status indicates that the test has been planned but not yet executed.

- "Extreme temperature points" refer to the minimum and maximum temperatures within each test category and subcategory;
- "Average test duration" is calculated by averaging the test durations for each temperature point;
- "Test category" and "test subcategory" are classifications of the tests, where a category might be "Thermal" and a subcategory might be "High Temperature Storage".

sql:
SELECT test_item
FROM tests
WHERE test_duration_hours = (
    SELECT MAX(test_duration_hours) FROM tests
);

